Last night was incredible! I had the pleasure of seeing my friends, both old and new performing songs from the late, great @davidbowie ❤️ A cool addition was that much of the performance was actually in 3D! 👓  Before the concert started, the creator of the Afro punk, @spoonersnofun spoke on black music, keep in mind the demographic of the audience. He was making some really valid points and speaking on how Bowie always paid homage to black artists and performers and gave credit where it was due. Of course some yt guy from the audience yells out “get to the music!” (That’s our version of “shut up and dribble”). That was followed by groans from the audience and then the announcer carried on.  The show was PURE magic! Shout out to my girl @kittenkuroi for absolutely sllllaaaayyying 🔥🔥🔥 Totally Grace Jones vibes ❤️ Love you girl! And of course to the one and only @vurnt22 🎸. @justinwarfield has one of the coolest voices and really brought the songs to life. @woodywoodstraw and @tonyaustindrums  held that bottom down and had me dancing all night! @ericmayronmusic 🎹  @drmaddvibe @brettfarkasmusic …..Ugh… I could go on and will come and write more on this unforgettable night. Thank you to all involved!! ❤️❤️❤️🔥🔥🔥 and shout out to my new friend @georgia.muldrow .. we had each other crackin up 😂😂😂🙏🙏🙏🎸💫💫💫

social_posts.post_text: Was a very surreal experience to perform at this year’s MET gala. Even more, to reunite with my @americanutopia bandmates and DB. I missed them. I’m especially happy that Lizzo was the guest performance, she and her band killed it 😜🥰🥰🥰I hope KL is somewhere enjoying that. It’s impossible for me to express the extremes I felt being there, especially in the world we are all in. A paradox. That evening the news came about the writers strike, time to stand in solidarity! Funny sidenote: Met Ms. Wintour at our rehearsal and she complimented the shirt I was wearing, of a dog playing a piano 😂… maybe I’ll be on the cover of Vogue now. 🐶

NYC! You were great! I missed you and know I surely will return one day when the time and opportunity are right. Here’s the shirt Anna Wintour complimented. She’d probably look pretty fly in it too 😘😃😃😃
❤️Mom

Happy Juneteenth Day! Hoping that more and more people learn, understand and respect the significance of this day, as it is a HUGE part of American history, for ALL Americans. It’s only recently become a federal holiday (though I find that bizarre, I personally prefer real systemic change to a holiday). So whether you’re BBQing, partying or simply enjoying a day off work (which many marginalized people can’t afford to do, ironic), please understand in your heart the significance of this day and reflect. Only then can we work towards building a true American utopia. #empathy #atonement #allyship #juneteenth (pages 2/3 by @ajabarber, thank you, I couldn’t have said it better 🙏🏾❤️) support a black owned business today or creative.

A GREAT AND INFORMATIVE READ. Excerpts from article: “Despite the challenges, musicians are fighting for better benefits. “It's clear that the entire music economy is really broken in so many ways. And I think a lot of people have been afraid to speak up about it because no one wants to say, ‘I'm poor in the music industry.’ But I think a lot of people realize nothing's going to move forward, and so people are honest about what they're actually having to do to make a living.”” ***Too many people (including some fellow musicians) still consider and treat pro musicians as “hobbyists”, though it takes waaaay longer to learn an instrument than to finish medical/law school. Music is essential! Who listened to zero music during the pandemic? ** You’d be surprised how low some major opportunities can be…. But often you’re literally made to sign NDAs to not disclose how little you earned. Too many musicians are desperate and agree to unlivable deals because of fear of replacement and they don’t realize the power they could have if united. When you accept an offer for low or cheap you’re not just doing a disservice to yourself, but the collective. Check out there full article at: https://www.kcrw.com/news/shows/press-play-with-madeleine-brand/ai-strikes-nbcuniversal-barbie/musicians-no-union. MORE MUSICIANS SHOULD BE FOLLOWING——-> @afm_union . Let’s fix this! We’re ready

We celebrated the life of @jamescaseysax this past Monday. People came from all over the world (literally) to pay their respects. I saw fellow Berklee friends I hadn’t seen in decades, decades. I met James’ parents, they reminded me of him so so much, I couldn’t hold back the tears. I simply cannot put into words the amount of love that was there. But thank you to @nikkidrums @reallouiscato and all the organizers of this beautiful event. Many musicians got up and played. @treyanastasio even played an incredible set. James was felt throughout the night and was surely smiling down on us. We love you James and will never forget you. ❤️❤️❤️ By the way, this first photo is of James’ biological and musical family. This was the crowd BEFORE doors opened to the public. Too many names to tag, but just look at all the lives he touched. We were all so blessed to know him.
Citizens of the planet. We speak the language of love and connectivity, not destruction. ❤️Repost by @denovo.agency

Last night I had the pleasure of joining a friend and checking out the sneak peak of #WeAreHereHulu was absolutely amazing. Directed by Melinda Maerker and EP David Miller. “We Live Here: The Midwest” profiles families who hope to stay in a part of the country they love, and where they have often established deep roots, while being a part of the LGBTQ+ community. I highly recommend watching this touching documentary that comes out December 6 on @hulu. Thank you to my friend and fellow Wisconsinite @thebrandonlim for the invite. In the meantime, enjoy our goofy photos from the after party. 🌈❤️🔥😍💫
